  "bib_entries": {
    "2527623": {
      "title": "Genetic algorithm and graph partitioning",
      "abstract": "Hybrid genetic algorithms (GAs) for the graph partitioning problem are described. The algorithms include a fast local improvement heuristic. One of the novel features of these algorithms is the schema preprocessing phase that improves GAs' space searching capability, which in turn improves the performance of GAs. Experimental tests on graph problems with published solutions showed that the new genetic algorithms performed comparable to or better than the multistart Kernighan-Lin algorithm and the simulated annealing algorithm. Analyses of some special classes of graphs are also provided showing the usefulness of schema preprocessing and supporting the experimental results."
    },
    "121504906": {
      "title": "The bandwidth minimization problem for caterpillars with hair length 3 is NP-complete",
      "abstract": "It is shown that the Bandwidth Minimization problem remains NP-complete even when restricted to “caterpillars with hairs of length at most three”. “Caterpillars” are special trees; they consist of a simple chain (the “body”) with various simple chains attached to thee vertices of the body (the attached chains are called “hairs”). A previous result in the literature shows that the bandwidth of caterpillars with hairs of length at most 2 can be found in $O( n\\log n )$ time (this Journal, 2 (1981), pp. 387–393). We also show that the bandwidth problem is NP-complete when restricted to caterpillars with at most one hair attached to each vertex of the body. The proof is relatively straightforward and thereby also provides an easier proof than found in (SIAM J. Appl. Math., 34 (1978), pp. 477–495) that the bandwidth problem is NP-complete for trees with maximum vertex degree 3."
    },
    "115386974": {
      "title": "Vertex and edge partitions of graphs",
      "abstract": "In this thesis I consider the $\\alpha$-edge and $\\alpha$-vertex graph partitioning problems. These problems will be viewed from four different perspectives. ::: First the complexity of finding good approximation algorithms for these problems will be considered. For general graphs it is shown that one cannot find an edge separator having size within $OPT+n\\sp{2-\\epsilon}$ for an n-vertex graph with an optimal solution of size OPT unless P = NP. For graphs with maximum degree 3 it is shown to be NP-hard to find a vertex separator of size $OPT+n\\sp{{1\\over2}-\\epsilon}.$ ::: Since the general edge and vertex partitioning problems are NP-hard this thesis will also consider solving these problems optimally for restricted classes of graphs. It will be shown that partial k-trees (k fixed) can be optimally edge partitioned in $O(n\\sp3)$ time. It will also be shown that series-parallel graphs can be optimally edge partitioned in $O(n\\sp2)$ time. For the vertex separator problem, I will show that if an n-vertex planar graph has an optimal vertex separator of size O(log n), then we can find an optimal vertex separator in polynomial time. This result generalizes to other problems that can be solved optimally on k-outerplanar graphs. Instances of these problems on planar graphs that have a small (i.e., O(log n)) optimal solution can be solved exactly in polynomial time. ::: Parallel algorithms are developed for edge partitioning series-parallel graphs and partial k-trees. The parallel algorithm for partial k-trees uses $O(n\\sp3)$ processors and runs in time O(log n log log n). For series-parallel graphs the number of processors needed is reduced to $O(n\\sp2)$ and the running time remains the same. ::: Also considered is the use of heuristics for solving edge and vertex partitioning problems. Data from an empirical study of a new heuristic that dramatically improves the performance of some popularly used methods will be presented. Various heuristic methods are compared on several different kinds of problems."
    }
